{"key":"processedPost-15461298","value":{"id":15461298,"first":15460193,"last":15462816,"when":1322971024,"utime":"12/04/11 05:57 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Kevin_X2 said:</b><br /><br />Misting is encouraged because supposedly one of the key pinning triggers is water evaporating from the surface of the cake. But, of course, the cakes are filled with water anyways and so evaporation is an ongoing process. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />Supposedly?<br /><br />Evaporation is the number one pinning trigger.<br /><br />Further, if proper fresh air exchange is taking place, the cakes will dry out in short order.&nbsp; This is commonly misunderstood, mostly due to earlier texts and guides which advised sealed terrariums, or 'a few air exchanges per hour', but such is insufficient for maximum performance.&nbsp; Constant fresh air is superior, and with a constant exchange of fresh air taking place, substrates will dry out in a few hours, require misting to replace that which was lost.<br /><br />An understanding of this concept is why experienced growers today consistently turn out flushes which would blow the minds of people just five or six years ago.<br />RR","title":"Re: What are the best indicators that it is time to mist cakes again?"}}